Lab 6: Linear Models – Regression vs. Classification
Overview
This lab explores the fundamental distinction between the two most common types of supervised learning: Regression (predicting numbers) and Classification (predicting categories). I implemented and compared two foundational models—Linear Regression and Logistic Regression—to solve different predictive challenges within the Titanic and Iris datasets.

Key Learning Objectives
Predicting Continuous Values: Used Linear Regression to predict passenger fares. I learned that regression isn't about being "right or wrong," but about minimizing the distance between the prediction and the actual value.

Binary & Multiclass Classification: Implemented Logistic Regression to categorize data points into discrete groups.

Performance Metrics:

Mean Squared Error (MSE): Used to measure the "average error" in numerical predictions.

Accuracy Score: Used to measure the "truth rate" in categorical predictions.

Model Interpretation: Analyzed Coefficients to understand which features (like Passenger Class) had the strongest positive or negative impact on the final prediction.

Tools & Libraries
Scikit-Learn: Used for LinearRegression, LogisticRegression, and error metrics.

Matplotlib: Used to visualize the "Line of Best Fit" for regression tasks.

Challenges & Insights
The Proximity Logic: A major insight was understanding why "Accuracy" is a bad metric for regression. If a fare is $50.00 and the model predicts $50.01, it is technically "wrong" (0% accurate), but scientifically excellent. This taught me to choose metrics based on the nature of the problem, not just the easiest number to read.

Coefficient Direction: I learned that a negative coefficient in a class-based model means that as the class number goes up (moving from 1st to 3rd class), the survival probability or fare price drops—quantifying the "wealth gap" I saw in Lab 4.

"Ranger" Connection
This lab is the "Engine Room" for my Microscope Buddy project. When the robot is moving the Z-axis, it uses Regression logic to predict the focal distance. When it sees an object and must decide if it is a "Cell" or a "Bubble," it uses Classification logic. Understanding this distinction allows me to build a robot that can both "measure" and "decide" autonomously.
